Let the DNA sequence of a gene be modelled by a discrete-time signal $g[n]$, where $n$ is the position of the nucleotide in the sequence. Suppose that the researcher is studying a gene therapy technique that modifies the DNA sequence according to a discrete-time linear time-invariant system with impulse response $h[n]$. 

Let $y[n]$ be the output of the system, i.e., the modified DNA sequence. The system is defined by the discrete-time convolution of $g[n]$ and $h[n]$:

$y[n] = (g * h)[n] = \sum_{k=-\infty}^{+\infty} g[k] \cdot h[n - k]$

Suppose that the DNA sequence $g[n]$ is given by 

$g[n] = \left\{
	\begin{array}{ll}
		1 & \mbox{if } n = 0 \\
		0 & \mbox{otherwise}
	\end{array}
\right.$

and the impulse response $h[n]$ is given by 

$h[n] = \left\{
	\begin{array}{ll}
		(-1)^n & \mbox{if } 0 \leq n \leq 4 \\
		0 & \mbox{otherwise}
	\end{array}
\right.$

Find a general formula for $y[n]$.
